  <!-- MODULE 1: YOUR GAP REPORT -->
  <div class="apn-r-section" id="apn-rec-m1" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-r-inner">
      <span class="apn-r-label">YOUR CURRENT STATE</span>
      <h2 class="apn-r-headline">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-r-divider"></div>

      <div id="apn-rec-score-context"></div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        The elite benchmark for recovery sits at 90 or above. Athletes at that level eat 25 to 30g of protein within 45 minutes of every training session without exception. They measure HRV daily and adjust training intensity based on trend data, not feel. They do at least one deliberate active recovery session per week. Their systemic inflammation markers, specifically C-reactive protein (CRP) and interleukin-6 (IL-6), are trending down rather than chronically elevated. They train hard and they rebuild completely. That combination is rare because most athletes are only doing one of the two.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-r-data-callout">
        <div class="apn-r-data-callout__stat">48 hours</div>
        <div class="apn-r-data-callout__desc">The window during which muscle protein synthesis remains elevated after a hard training session. Most athletes fail to supply adequate leucine-rich protein through this entire window, meaning they are funding the training stimulus but not completing the repair transaction.</div>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        The performance tax you are paying is cumulative. Each session that does not fully recover compresses the starting point of the next. After 3 to 4 weeks of incomplete recovery, the cumulative deficit is not just fatigue. It is structural: satellite cell activation is blunted, glycogen replenishment is partial, and your neuromuscular output is operating against a rising baseline of inflammatory markers that have not cleared. You feel like you should be adapting. You are not. Not fully.
      </p>

      <!-- Tier-conditional framing -->
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="border-left:4px solid #22C55E; background:#F0FDF4; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">This is the most important system change you will make this month. Training creates the stimulus. Recovery is where the adaptation actually happens. You cannot separate them. One without the other is just accumulated wear. Fix this first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B; background:#FFFBEB; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Your training output is consistent. Your recovery is the bottleneck. You are training hard enough to demand serious repair but your post-training nutrition and recovery architecture are not matching that demand. Close this gap and your training investment starts paying full dividends.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="border-left:4px solid #06A5C5; background:#F0FBFF; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">You are in the optimization zone. Recovery basics are in place but you are leaving precision on the table. HRV tracking, leucine threshold accuracy, and anti-inflammatory protocol timing are the variables that take you from solid recovery to complete recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="border-left:4px solid #8B5CF6; background:#F5F3FF; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">At your level, recovery is a precision variable. Your HRV trend, your resting HR pattern, your joint health markers, and your post-training protein timing windows all matter at the level of minutes and milligrams. The margin you are looking for is in the details of this protocol.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="border-left:4px solid #EF4444; background:#FEF2F2; padding:20px 24px; margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION LEVEL</p>
        <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Protect the architecture. At Champion level, recovery degradation is the primary risk to sustained performance. It is not intensity or motivation. It is the slow erosion of recovery quality that eventually breaks training continuity. This protocol is your maintenance and protection system.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Win -->
      <div style="background:#0D0D0D; border-radius:4px; padding:28px 32px; margin:40px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:4px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:12px;">YOUR QUICK WIN TODAY</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:16px; color:#F8FAFB; line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:0;">
          After your next training session, within 45 minutes: consume 25 to 30g of protein that contains at least 2.5g of leucine. This triggers the mTOR (mechanistic target of rapamycin) pathway, the primary switch for initiating muscle protein synthesis. Without hitting the leucine threshold, protein is metabolized but mTOR does not fully activate. If you train today, this action captures the highest-yield recovery window available. A shaker with 30g of whey protein isolate contains approximately 2.8 to 3.2g of leucine, which is above threshold. Do this for 7 consecutive post-training sessions and measure whether your soreness duration changes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 2: WHY THIS IS COSTING YOU -->
  <div class="apn-r-section" id="apn-rec-m2" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-r-inner">
      <span class="apn-r-label">THE SCIENCE</span>
      <h2 class="apn-r-headline">The Mechanism Behind Your Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-r-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        Recovery is not a feeling. It is a sequence of specific biological processes that either complete or do not. Understanding what those processes are tells you exactly which variables to target. There are four that matter most.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        <strong>Muscle protein synthesis (MPS):</strong> Training creates micro-damage to muscle fibers. The repair signal is muscle protein synthesis, driven by the mTOR pathway. MPS peaks in the 0 to 2 hour window post-training and remains elevated for 24 to 48 hours. The trigger for mTOR activation is leucine: you need a minimum of 2.5 to 3g of leucine per meal to fully activate the pathway. Under that threshold, some synthesis occurs but the anabolic response is blunted. Most athletes either miss the post-training window entirely or consume 10 to 15g of protein rather than the 25 to 30g required to hit leucine threshold.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        <strong>The inflammation cascade:</strong> Resistance training triggers a controlled inflammatory response. IL-6 (interleukin-6) is released from contracting muscle fibers within minutes of training. TNF-alpha rises shortly after. This acute inflammation is adaptive: it signals satellite cells to mobilize and initiates the repair sequence. The problem is chronically elevated inflammation. When IL-6 and TNF-alpha are elevated persistently (due to poor recovery, insufficient sleep, dietary inflammatory load, or accumulated training debt), they become catabolic rather than anabolic. The same cytokines that should drive repair start inhibiting it. The body cannot distinguish between productive stress and destructive stress when the baseline is already high.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        <strong>HRV as the recovery indicator:</strong> Heart rate variability measures the variation in time between consecutive heartbeats and reflects the balance between sympathetic (stress) and parasympathetic (recovery) nervous system activity. Low HRV means your body is in a state of sympathetic dominance: it is stressed, not recovered. A declining HRV trend over days or weeks is the earliest objective signal of accumulated recovery debt, often visible 48 to 72 hours before subjective performance drops. It is your best single data point for whether your body is absorbing training or accumulating damage.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        <strong>Satellite cell activation:</strong> Satellite cells are the stem cells of muscle tissue. After training, they are activated by IGF-1 (insulin-like growth factor 1) and by mechanical tension signals. They divide, differentiate, and fuse to damaged muscle fibers to repair and add myonuclei. This process requires adequate protein, IGF-1 availability, and time. Colostrum contains bovine IGF-1 at clinically significant concentrations. This is the mechanism behind its use in recovery protocols.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-r-data-callout">
        <div class="apn-r-data-callout__stat">20%</div>
        <div class="apn-r-data-callout__desc">Reduction in next-session strength output measured when post-training protein is delayed beyond 2 hours versus consumed within 45 minutes. The training session happened. The adaptation did not. That is what a missed recovery window costs.</div>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">
        The compounding effect moves across three pillars simultaneously. Incomplete recovery means inadequate sleep quality (elevated inflammatory markers disrupt slow-wave sleep). Poor sleep means reduced GH output and higher cortisol the next morning. Higher cortisol is directly catabolic to muscle tissue, meaning the muscle you trained to build is being broken down by the hormonal environment your poor recovery created. It is a three-way drag that most athletes only attribute to "overtraining."
      </p>

      <div class="apn-r-warning">
        <span class="apn-r-warning__label">COMMON MISTAKE</span>
        <p>Training through declining HRV and calling it mental toughness. A 3-day HRV drop of 10 to 15% below your baseline is not an opportunity to push harder. It is a signal that the sympathetic nervous system is dominant and your body is not in an anabolic state. Training at high intensity when HRV is suppressed does not build fitness. It deepens the debt. Reduce intensity to 60 to 70% of maximum effort, keep the movement, and let the HRV recover before pushing hard again.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tier-conditional cost block -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif; font-size:22px; color:#0D0D0D; margin:40px 0 16px;">What This Gap Is Costing You Right Now</h3>

      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="rookie">
        <p class="apn-r-body">As a Rookie, your recovery gap means that most of the training you are doing is not converting into the adaptation it should. You are accumulating fatigue faster than you are accumulating fitness. The training stimulus is right. The recovery architecture to harvest it is not in place yet. Building this system is the highest leverage change you can make.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="competitor">
        <p class="apn-r-body">At Competitor level, your recovery gap is suppressing your training ceiling. You can train harder but your body cannot fully absorb it. Your post-training protein timing and your inflammation management are likely the two largest gaps. Close both and your training volume can meaningfully increase while recovery time decreases.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <p class="apn-r-body">At Athlete level, your recovery gap is a precision drag. Your big-picture recovery is in place but the detail that separates good recovery from complete recovery is leucine threshold accuracy, HRV-guided training adjustments, and anti-inflammatory protocol consistency. These are not dramatic changes. They are the 5 to 10% improvements that are invisible in a single session and significant across a 12-week training block.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="elite">
        <p class="apn-r-body">At Elite level, your recovery gap is costing you the adaptation that separates your current level from the next. You are training at high enough intensity that incomplete recovery compounds fast. Joint inflammation that does not fully clear between sessions becomes chronic. HRV suppression that persists for 2 to 3 weeks shifts from temporary debt to a structural overtraining state. The precision targets in this protocol are exactly what you need.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="champion">
        <p class="apn-r-body">At Champion level, any degradation in your recovery system is a direct threat to training continuity. You have built something significant. The cost of a poor recovery month is not just fitness regression. It is the disruption to the training schedule and competition preparation that took years to construct. Protect this with the same seriousness you bring to the training itself.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 3: THE DIAGNOSIS -->
  <div class="apn-r-section" id="apn-rec-m3" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-r-inner">
      <span class="apn-r-label">SELF-ASSESSMENT</span>
      <h2 class="apn-r-headline">Identify Your Specific Recovery Problem</h2>
      <div class="apn-r-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">Your quiz score gives us the what. This assessment identifies the why. Check every symptom that applies to your last 14 days of training. Be specific. The protocol that follows is calibrated to what you identify here.</p>

