  <!-- MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL -->
  <div class="apn-r-section" id="apn-rec-m4" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-r-inner">
      <span class="apn-r-label">THE PROTOCOL</span>
      <h2 class="apn-r-headline">Your 30-Day Recovery Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-r-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-r-body">Four weeks. One gap. Here is exactly what to do. The sequence matters: protein timing is Week 1 because it is the highest leverage variable. Everything else amplifies what this single habit establishes.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week__header">WEEK ONE</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__title">Lock Post-Training Protein Timing</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__focus">FOCUS: MPS WINDOW ACTIVATION</div>

        <p class="apn-r-body">Every session you train without hitting 25 to 30g of protein within 45 minutes is a missed repair transaction. The training demand happened. The recovery supply did not arrive in time. This week fixes that. Every session. No exceptions.</p>

        <ul class="apn-r-action-list">
          <li><strong>25 to 30g of leucine-rich protein within 45 minutes of ending every training session.</strong> The MPS peak occurs 0 to 2 hours post-training and begins declining after that. The mTOR pathway requires a minimum of 2.5 to 3g of leucine per feeding to fully activate. A quality whey protein isolate contains approximately 10 to 11% leucine by weight, meaning 28g of protein provides approximately 2.8g leucine, which is above threshold. Have the shaker ready before you start training. Mix it during your cooldown. Drink it within 45 minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>A second protein feeding within 2 hours of the first.</strong> MPS stays elevated for up to 48 hours, but it requires repeated leucine threshold feedings to sustain. The first post-training protein initiates the mTOR cascade. The second feeding 1.5 to 2 hours later sustains it. This does not need to be a shake. A whole food meal with 25 to 30g of protein is better. The timing is what matters.</li>
          <li><strong>Total daily protein: 0.7 to 1.0g per pound of bodyweight, distributed across 4 feedings minimum.</strong> Protein distribution matters more than total intake for MPS. 4 feedings of 30g each is superior to 2 feedings of 60g for activating MPS across the day. Check your actual intake for 3 consecutive days. Most athletes are 30 to 40% below target.</li>
          <li><strong>Prepare your post-training protein before you leave for the gym.</strong> Decision fatigue is the real barrier. If the shake is ready and in your gym bag, you will drink it. If it requires preparation after training, you may not. Remove the friction entirely.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Tier blocks -->
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">One non-negotiable: 25 to 30g of protein within 45 minutes of every training session. Start there. Do not add the second feeding or distribution tracking until this is locked. One habit. Lock it. Then build on it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Post-training shake within 45 minutes and a whole food protein meal within 2 hours. Those are your two targets this week. Track your daily total to confirm you are at 0.7 to 1.0g per pound. Do not add anything else until these two are consistent every training day.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">All four actions this week. Also begin logging your post-training soreness on a 1 to 10 scale each morning for 7 days. This is your Week 1 baseline. You will compare it to Week 4. Track your HRV if you have a device. You are building a data picture, not just executing a protocol.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Audit your current post-training timing with precision. Not "within an hour." Within 45 minutes, with leucine content verified. Start daily HRV tracking this week if you have not. Pull your 7-day HRV average. That is your baseline for the 30-day protocol. Every other variable will be measured against it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Review your protein timing for any recent drift. Travel, schedule changes, and competition weeks are common causes of timing slippage that athletes do not consciously track. Verify every session this week. If your timing is already locked within 45 minutes consistently, confirm your daily total and distribution are accurate.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="apn-r-assignment">
          <span class="apn-r-assignment__label">YOUR ASSIGNMENT</span>
          <p>Before your next training session: prepare a shaker bottle with 28 to 30g of whey protein isolate powder. Put it in your bag. After your last working set, mix it and drink it before you leave the gym. Repeat for every session this week. Track whether your 48-hour soreness changes by the end of 7 days.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week__header">WEEK TWO</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__title">Add Active Recovery and HRV Tracking</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__focus">FOCUS: PARASYMPATHETIC ACTIVATION AND RECOVERY DATA</div>

        <p class="apn-r-body">Protein timing is locked. Now add the two variables that accelerate the repair process between sessions: deliberate active recovery and objective HRV measurement. Passive rest is less effective than active recovery for clearing metabolic waste and returning the nervous system to parasympathetic dominance.</p>

        <ul class="apn-r-action-list">
          <li><strong>One 20-minute active recovery session on every rest day.</strong> Not a workout. Deliberate low-intensity movement at 50 to 60% of maximum heart rate. Walking, light cycling, easy swimming, or yoga. The mechanism: low-intensity movement increases local blood flow to muscle tissue, accelerates lactate clearance, reduces IL-6 and TNF-alpha concentrations more quickly than complete rest, and activates the parasympathetic nervous system. This is not extra training. It is recovery work.</li>
          <li><strong>Start daily HRV tracking this week if you have not already.</strong> Take a 60-second reading first thing in the morning, before getting out of bed. Use Whoop, Oura, Garmin, or the free app HRV4Training. Record every reading. Your goal is to identify your personal baseline and to begin seeing the correlation between training days, recovery actions, and HRV response. You cannot manage what you cannot measure.</li>
          <li><strong>Post-training cold water exposure: 10 to 15 minutes in 55 to 65F water within 2 hours of finishing a hard session.</strong> Cold water immersion reduces post-exercise inflammation markers including IL-6 and CRP, and activates the vagus nerve, shifting the autonomic nervous system toward parasympathetic recovery. A cold shower will not replicate full immersion, but contrast therapy (30 seconds cold, 90 seconds hot, repeated 3 times ending cold) is a practical alternative.</li>
          <li><strong>Reduce training intensity on any day when your HRV is 10% or more below your 7-day rolling average.</strong> This is a data-driven decision, not a feeling. If your HRV is 55 and your 7-day average is 65, you are 15% suppressed. Keep the session but reduce load to 60 to 70% of maximum. You will adapt better over the month than you would by grinding through full-intensity sessions on a suppressed nervous system.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Tier blocks -->
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#22C55E; margin-bottom:8px;">ROOKIE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Add one 20-minute walk on each rest day. That is it. Walking at a comfortable pace is active recovery. No equipment, no gym, no tracking required. Just movement on the days you are not training.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#F59E0B; margin-bottom:8px;">COMPETITOR THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Active recovery session on rest days and start HRV tracking. You do not need a Whoop or Oura. The free HRV4Training app works. Take 7 readings this week. At the end of the week you will have a baseline. That baseline is your most important data point going into Week 3.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#06A5C5; margin-bottom:8px;">ATHLETE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">All four actions. Add contrast therapy after at least two sessions this week. Plot your HRV readings each day. By the end of the week you should begin seeing a pattern: training days suppressing HRV, recovery actions restoring it. That pattern tells you how fast your nervous system is recovering and whether your current training load is sustainable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#8B5CF6; margin-bottom:8px;">ELITE THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">HRV-guided training is your primary tool this week. Calculate your 7-day rolling average. Set a decision rule: if daily HRV is more than 10% below average, intensity drops to 65%. If within range, train as planned. At your training volume, this single adjustment is likely the highest-leverage change you have not yet consistently applied. Remove the subjective decision. Use the data.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:4px; margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif; font-size:10px; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:3px; color:#EF4444; margin-bottom:8px;">CHAMPION THIS WEEK</p>
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin:0;">Active recovery and HRV monitoring should already be in your system. The precision target this week is cold exposure consistency. If you are doing it only sometimes, make it non-negotiable after every hard session this week. Compare your next-morning HRV on nights following cold exposure versus nights without. The data will tell you whether it is worth keeping as permanent infrastructure.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="apn-r-assignment">
          <span class="apn-r-assignment__label">YOUR ASSIGNMENT</span>
          <p>Schedule your active recovery sessions now. Open your calendar and block 20 minutes on each rest day this week labeled "Recovery." Not optional. Not "if I feel like it." Scheduled. Also download an HRV app today and take your first reading tomorrow morning immediately upon waking. Begin building the data picture.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week__header">WEEK THREE</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__title">Add the Anti-Inflammatory Protocol</div>
        <div class="apn-r-week__focus">FOCUS: INFLAMMATION MANAGEMENT AND COLOSTRUM INTRODUCTION</div>

        <p class="apn-r-body">Protein timing is locked. Active recovery and HRV tracking are in progress. Now introduce the biochemical support that targets the inflammatory cascade directly. This week your recovery architecture becomes complete.</p>

        <!-- Scripture block -->
        <div class="apn-r-scripture">
          <p class="apn-r-scripture__verse">"Do you not know that your bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit, who is in you, whom you have received from God? You are not your own; you were bought at a price. Therefore honor God with your bodies."</p>
          <p class="apn-r-scripture__ref">1 Corinthians 6:19-20</p>
        </div>

        <p class="apn-r-body">Recovery is not a luxury. It is stewardship. The body you have been given is capable of more than you have demanded of it so far, but that capacity requires care as much as it requires training. This week you are adding the tools that allow you to train harder and recover completely, which is the combination that honors both the discipline and the gift.</p>

        <ul class="apn-r-action-list">
          <li><strong>Colostrum, 2g daily with your first meal.</strong> Bovine colostrum contains IGF-1 (insulin-like growth factor 1) at clinically significant concentrations. IGF-1 activates satellite cells, the muscle stem cells responsible for fiber repair and hypertrophy. Colostrum also contains secretory IgA for gut lining repair, which is relevant because high-intensity training increases intestinal permeability, allowing inflammatory molecules into systemic circulation. The gut lining restoration reduces the total inflammatory load your recovery system must manage. Take 2g daily consistently. Effects accumulate over 3 to 4 weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Turmeric (curcumin), 500mg with black pepper extract, with your largest meal.</strong> Curcumin inhibits the NF-kB (nuclear factor kappa-light-chain-enhancer of activated B cells) pathway, which is the primary transcription factor driving IL-6 and TNF-alpha production in chronically inflamed tissue. Black pepper extract (piperine, 5 to 10mg) increases curcumin bioavailability by 2000% by inhibiting its rapid hepatic metabolism. Without piperine, most curcumin passes through without being absorbed. Verify your product contains piperine before taking it.</li>
          <li><strong>Omega-3 fatty acids: 2 to 3g of EPA plus DHA daily with food.</strong> EPA (eicosapentaenoic acid) is a direct precursor to resolvin and protectin compounds, which are specialized pro-resolving mediators that actively terminate the inflammatory cascade. They do not just block inflammation. They resolve it. This is mechanistically different from NSAIDs, which suppress the acute phase but do not complete the resolution. Higher EPA intake has also been associated with reduced delayed-onset muscle soreness (DOMS) duration in endurance and resistance-trained athletes.</li>
          <li><strong>Eliminate alcohol for this week.</strong> Alcohol suppresses protein synthesis by up to 24% and elevates systemic inflammation markers independently of training. If you are taking colostrum and turmeric to manage inflammation while simultaneously consuming alcohol, you are working against yourself. One week clean. Observe the difference.</li>
        </ul>

